observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our previous recommendations that the: 

a. Municipal Mayor direct the Inventory Committee to develop a concrete plan for the conduct of a complete physical inventory of PPEs within a set time frame, and to submit a properly accomplished RPCPPE with complete and appropriate details annually;

b. Municipal Accountant analyze each PPE account, especially those with recorded lump sum balances for proper identification, and exert efforts to retrieve documents/records to identify all depreciable PPEs, and effect the necessary adjustment to provide depreciation and any impairment in accordance with IPSAS 17 – Property, Plant and Equipment;

c. Municipal Accountant and General Service Officer prepare and maintain complete and detailed reports of PPEs, and coordinate and regularly reconcile their records; and

d. Municipal Mayor, through the Municipal Accountant, GSO, and Inventory Committee, consider the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances by undertaking procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

Moreover, we recommended that: 

e. The Municipal Accountant: 

e.1. Devise a complete and appropriate lapsing schedule for computing Depreciation Expense for the year 2024; 

e.2. Prepare and maintain PPELC and LRNLC to account for all the Municipality’s PPEs; 

e.3. Reclassify semi-expendable properties recorded as PPE and apply the updated capitalization threshold retroactively in accordance with COA Circular No. 2024-006 dated March 14, 2024; and

f. Municipal General Services Officer prepare and maintain all required forms, records, and reports for semi-expendable properties under COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022, with the complete details to establish control and safeguards on supply and property management.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Management comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015, specifically: 

a. Municipal Engineer provide the GSO and Accounting Office with a complete description and cost breakdown of each road component to support the preparation of the RLRN and the Road Map; 

b. GSO maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and prepare a complete and accurate RLRN showing all required details; 

c. Inventory Committee conduct a complete and timely physical inventory of road networks and submit the RPCLRN to the Audit Team and Accounting Office not later than January 31 of each year; and 

d. Municipal Accountant include in the Notes to Financial Statements the required disclosure for Road Networks, and prepare and maintain the LRNLC, reconciling it with the RPCLRN to support the Road Network balances presented in the financial statements.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Accountant: 

a. Exert diligent efforts to retrieve all records related to the balances under the Due to NGAs account to determine the necessary details of the funds, such as the Source Agency, purpose, and nature of the fund balances, and disclose such details in the Notes to Financial Statements; 

b. Reconcile the amount of obligations or unliquidated fund transfers with the concerned government agencies; 

c. Properly liquidate the amount in accordance with the terms and conditions governing the transferred funds; otherwise, cause the return of the balance to the Source Agency or remit to the Bureau of Treasury if so stipulated, or make necessary adjustments, if warranted, duly supported by relevant documents; and 

d. Analyze the Due to NGAs account, determine any dormant balances for ten years, and apply for authority to write-off in accordance with the procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023.

a. Municipal Mayor, thru the Municipal Engineering Office, undertake the appropriate correction works for the noted defects of the subject infrastructure projects as recommended by the STAS and demand full reimbursement of corresponding expenses (not lower than the computed cost deficiency) from the parties found liable without prejudice to the filing of appropriate administrative, civil, and/or criminal charges against the responsible persons as well as the forfeiture of warranty securities posted in favor of the Municipality in accordance with Section 62.2.4 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184;

b. Municipal Engineer submit proof of corrective actions undertaken by the Municipality on the major defects noted by the STAS, together with proof of reimbursements made from the responsible parties;

c. Municipal Engineer consider placing doors/gates to the two constructed units of engine pump rooms in the Sanitary Landfill at Barangay Rosacara for safety purposes; and

d. Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Accountant, with the assistance of Municipal Engineer, to compute and demand liquidated damages from the contractors in default for the delay in completing the subject projects.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the concerned officials: 

a. Remit the amount of ₱3,311.30 to the National Treasury representing undisbursed LGSF-SBDP NTF-ELCAC funds; 

b. Explain the noted deficiencies and submit the lacking documents to substantiate compliance with LBC No. 154; 

c. Review the paid payrolls of Barangays Proper Tuguisan and Conrazon, and cause the immediate return of the unutilized amount of ₱12,000.00 to the DSWD; and 

d. Analyze the SL for social pension under the Due to NGAs account, trace the details of the ₱10,000.00 year-end balance, and cause the immediate return of the amount to DSWD or other appropriate Source Agency.

We recommended that the:
Local Finance Committee and Chairman, Committee on Appropriation- Sangguniang Bayan Member:
submit justification on the authority used (Resolution instead of Ordinance) allowing the changes made in the LDRRMF Annual Budget to appropriate funds for the repatriation of LSI, ROFs and others program totaling ₱3,700,000.00;
provide explanation on non-compliance with the recommendation of the PFC to prepare supplemental budget using the cited source of funds to appropriate funds for identified PPAs in AO No. 01, s. 2020; 
ensure compliance with the pertinent provisions of RA No. 7160 regarding the instrument required for authority in effecting changes in the Annual Budget; and
revisit Budget Operations Manual for LGUs to ensure that budgeting process is strictly followed. 
Municipal Budget Officer submit explanation for allowing further disbursement of fund from ConLA LDRRMF despite the declaration of AO No. 01, s. 2020 as inoperative in its entirety by the SP; 
Local Finance Committee ensure the budgeted amount for each PPAs shall not exceed the amount stated in the Annual/Supplemental Investment Program; and
Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer explain the excess disbursement of ₱64,099.75 out of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF in trust fund for COVID-19 related expenses.

We recommended that the:

Inventory Committee (i) conduct a complete physical count and technical valuation of the property, plant and equipment to establish existence, ownership and condition of the properties for the year especially for the local road network to determine the current value of the road components to facilitate the preparation of the RPCLRN; (ii) ensure that the required details in the reports were accurately and completely filled out; and (iii) ensure the preparation and submission of RPCPPE for all PPE accounts; 

Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate (i) coordinate and prepare supporting schedules to facilitate the proper reconciliation of the property accounts and establishment of actual existence, ownership and condition of the properties especially the previous year’s PPE acquisitions; (ii) prepare and maintain appropriate property records and reports for all PPE accounts especially for the Road Networks; and (iii) coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to complete the maintenance of a road map with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; 

Municipal Engineer prepare a schedule of the Local Roads indicating therein the cost of each Road Network Component such as road lot, road pavement, drainage and slope protection structures, and other miscellaneous structures to be submitted to the GSO and Accounting Office. Moreover, subsequent road projects of the Municipality should clearly indicate the separate cost of each road component for easy reference. The Engineering Office is also vested to determine the life of the Local Roads taking into consideration the design, type of users, and volume of users of the roads. Such detail should also be included in the schedule of Local Roads to serve basis for the depreciation of the Road Components to be applied by the Accounting Office;

GSO-Designate prepare and maintain RPCLRN to account for the Local Roads to be reconciled with the RPI to be prepared by the Municipal Accountant; and

Municipal Accountant (i) classify all completed infrastructure projects in its appropriate PPE accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-008; and (ii) prepare separate subsidiary ledgers for the determined cost of the Road Network Components, and thereafter provide for the depreciation of each Road Component based from the records to be prepared by the Engineering Office to establish proper valuation of the Road Network.

We recommended that:

the BAC Chairman and the members of the BAC explain the noted observations in the procurement process relative to the procurement of services for the preparation of technical survey description and plans for the proposed subdivision;

the Management require the Dayanghirang Surveying and Development Office to submit the necessary supporting documents as part of the performance of the scope of work as indicated in the contract agreement in support to the claim for partial payment and the BAC Secretariat submit the lacking bid documents to support the propriety of the disbursement and to avoid suspension/ disallowance in audit;

the Management seek justification from the DSDO relative to the delay in the delivery of the expected output which was the Consolidation/Subdivision Plan approved by the DENR-LMS and LRA which will eventually be used in the implementation of housing project for the Municipal officials and employees;

the Municipal Accountant compute for the liquidated damages incurred for the delay in the delivery of services and make a formal demand against the supplier for the payment of the amount computed as required in Section 68 of Revised IRR of RA 9184; and

the Management strictly comply with the provisions of the Section 4(6) of P.D. 1445, COA Memorandum No. 2005-027 and Revised IRR of RA 9184 relative to the procurement of consulting services for the preparation of technical survey description and plans.

We also recommended that the:

the Municipal Budget Officer provide justification relative to the non-reversion to the unappropriated surplus of the CY 2015 appropriation for Survey and Titling Expenses under MOOE as required in Section 322 of RA 7160; and

the Municipal Accountant indicate the source of fund in the future issuances of Certificate of Availability of Funds for proper audit of the same.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant and Treasurer reconcile their cash records and settle the disparity in the balances of cash accounts per GL and cashbooks; 

Municipal Accountant (i) conduct detailed review and checking of bank records/reports and request for the necessary documents to support the recording of the reconciling items, if any; (ii) exert effort to substantiate the identified reconciling items and prepare the necessary adjustments; (iii) review the long outstanding/stale checks specifically those checks without identified payees, and require the Municipal Treasurer to cancel the unclaimed stale checks and furnish the Accountant with the original DVs and its supporting documents, for the preparation of the JEV following the procedures prescribed under the Manual on the NGAS Manual for LGUs to ensure recording of the cancellation; and (iv) ensure the petty cash fund is fully liquidated at yearend.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

BAC Chairperson through the BAC Secretariat to (a) comment on the (i) delay in the issuance of NOA, contract agreement and posting of performance security; (ii) absence of proof of posting of NOA and NTP in the PhilGEPS; and (iii) undated bidding documents; and (b) ensure that Bid Evaluation Report and all other documents are properly dated in compliance with Sections 32.4 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184. Henceforth, abide with the provisions of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 particularly, Section 37.1.2 and 37.1.3 on the issuance of NOA, Section 37.2.1 on the posting of Performance Security, and Sections 37.1.6 and 37.4.2 in the posting of the NOA and NTP in the PhilGEPS;

Municipal Engineer to provide explanation for the approval of work suspension due to weather condition for the Construction of Multi-Purpose Center Phase I at Barangay Sumagui;

GSO and the Inspectorate Team ensure that goods and other supplies delivered were complete and in good condition thru proper inspection and evaluation. Likewise, ensure that inspection and acceptance report were completely and accurately be filled-out; and

Municipal Accountant and the concerned municipal officials (i) comment on the doubtful details noted in the supporting documents; (ii) submit the lacking documents for audit purposes and (iii) ensure that future claims are supported with the documents as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

Municipal Engineer provide satisfactory explanation in the grant of suspension of work for the Concreting of Pre-Stressed Bridge and Construction of Roads Alcadesma to Rosacara;

Municipal Accountant review the entries made relevant to the above projects and effect the necessary entries, if warranted, and ensure compliance with COA Circular No. 2015-009 in recording similar transactions in the books of the MGB;

BAC Chairperson through the BAC Secretariat provide: (i) explanation on the noted delays in the execution of the contract agreement and ensure compliance to the provisions of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 in future transactions; and (ii) justification on the noted absence of the date on Bid Evaluation Report.

BAC Secretariat, Municipal Accountant and the concerned municipal officials and employees: (i) provide explanation on the noted doubtful details on the supporting documents; and (ii) submit the lacking necessary documents to support the propriety and validity of the disbursements and ensure that claims for the future transactions were supported with necessary documents before payment.

We reiterated our recommendation that the:

MDRRMC (i) properly plan for the PPAs out of LDRRMF and observe strict compliance with the time frame set by regulations in the preparation and operationalization of the LDRRMFIP to facilitate effective utilization of the LDRRMF in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-002; (ii) evaluate the PPAs under the unexpended GF-LDRRMF capital outlay and TF-DRRM, and reprogram the fund as deemed necessary to improve disaster resiliency of the MGB, and include the same in the LDRRMFIP to establish its propriety in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-002; and (iii) in the conduct of planning, (a) properly classify the PPAs according to its nature of disbursement; (b) provide specific, measurable, achievable, realistic, and time-bound performance indicators to facilitate proper assessment of the DRRM capacity of the Municipality; (c) provide specific time-frame for the implementation of PPAs to facilitate strategic execution and monitoring of disaster-responsive measures programmed under the LDRRMFIP; and (d) review the identified PPAs in the LDRRMFIP and evaluate taking into consideration priorities, needs, and desired outcomes of the Municipality and its constituents, and make amendments thereto as deemed necessary, to facilitate realization and implementation of disaster-responsive and resilient projects; 

MDRRMO, Municipal Engineer and BAC fast track the implementation of the PPAs under LDRRMF by monitoring the period of its implementation and if applicable, implement the PPAs in the year it was programmed and appropriated to improve the capacity of the MGB to cope with potential hazards and disasters;

Municipal Accountant and Budget Officer revert the unexpended 70% LDRRMF-CO amounting to ₱3.59 million and the misclassified CO under the unspent 70% LDRRMF-MOOE totaling ₱600,000.00 to the GF in accordance with Section 5.1.11 of COA Circular No. 2012-002, and thereafter, provide proper disclosure of the DRRMF utilization and balances in the Notes to Financial Statements in accordance with Section 5.1.16 of the same circular for fair presentation; and

Municipal Accountant and the concerned Municipal Officials submit the lacking documents for audit purposes relevant to the procured Galvanized Iron (G.I.) sheets and ensure that future claims are supported with the documents as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001 to avoid audit suspension and/or disallowance.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the GAD Focal person and GAD key personnel to:

ensure the submission of GPB and AR on or before March 31 to the DILG Provincial Office pursuant to Section 4.0 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01, amending Section C.5 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC 2013-01;

ensure changes in the GPB are well reflected in the GAD AR pursuant to Annex E of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01; 

facilitate the preparation of the GAD Agenda as well as the updating and completion of the needed data for a functional GAD database pursuant to PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended by PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 as basis in the preparation of the annual GPB and AR;

ensure and monitor attendance of the GPFS members to GAD required trainings to capacitate and enhance their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD related laws and GAD-related tools, among others; and

facilitate the formulation Municipal GAD Code and its Implementing Rules and Regulations and ensure compliance of the same for its effective implementation.

We recommended that the:

MDC with the assistance of the MPDO reassess the necessity of pursuing the unimplemented PPAs of prior years, otherwise reprogram the same to more needed developmental projects. The Council should also properly plan, including specific identification of projects to be implemented and prioritize all activities to be implemented during the year;

MBO and MDC ensure that sufficient fund will be appropriated for the complete implementation of the identified projects;

Officials and employees concerned re-visit the policy on award and implementation of contract as prescribed in the RIRR of RA No. 9184;

BAC, Municipal Engineer and GSO provide reasonable explanation for the noted deficiencies in contract and actual project implementation;

Municipal Engineer and Accountant evaluate the delay incurred in project completion of certain projects as presented in Annex “K” and compute for any liquidated damages;

BAC Secretariat, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant submit the lacking supporting documents within five (5) days upon receipt hereof to support the propriety and validity of the disbursements made to avoid suspension and/or disallowance of the subjected transactions;

Municipal Accountant and Treasurer ensure that future claims be supported with complete documentation as required by Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445, Annex C of COA Circular No. 2009-001 and RA 9184 and its Revised IRR; and

BAC and Municipal Accountant require the posting of warranty securities for infrastructure projects in accordance with the prescribed rate under Section 62.2.3.3 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 to guarantee that the contractor shall perform his responsibilities in case of any structural defects/ failures within the prescribed period.

We recommended that the:

Management refrain from splitting government contracts and strictly abide with the procurement law known as RA 9184 and its IRR;

Municipal Engineer and MPDC monitor the implementation of the project and likewise ensure its timely completion to provide greater benefits to constituents;

Municipal Engineer submit Statement of work accomplished for the delivered materials on October 28, 2016 and explanation as to the whereabouts of those materials delivered on October 28, 2016 since the project could have been completed on July 9, 2016;

Municipal Accountant and BAC members and TWGs submit all the lacking documents within five days to support the propriety and validity of the disbursement made totaling ₱941,016.00 to avoid suspension and/or disallowance in audit, and further ensure that future claims be supported with complete documentation as required by Section 4 of P.D. 1445 and RA 9184 and its IRR; and

Municipal Accountant and Treasurer refrain from paying claims with incomplete documentation.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor and Officials observe strictly the austerity measures set by DILG and minimize attendance to “Lakbay-Aral”, instead, appropriate funds to programs/projects/ activities that will bring immediate socio-economic benefits among its local constituents;

Municipal SWDO and Accountant and other concerned Officials submit the following documents to facilitate audit as to legality and propriety of the disbursement; 

Justification as to excess payments to hotel and food since only 97 instead of 120 participants joined the Lakbay-Aral;

Justification as to why the “Lakbay-Aral” was made to Baguio City without inclusion of such travel to the Project Design, much more why it was held on Saturday, a nonworking day;

Certificate of Appearance from Host LGUs;

Terminal Report of Travel duly received by the DILG Regional Office;

Photo Documentation of the actual project implementation;

Document containing approval by the Host LGUs and the DILG from the Municipal and Regional Offices; and

Itineraries of Travel and Reports of Travel completed of the 97 participants of Lakbay-Aral in support for their claims of per diem and explain why the participants still claimed for incidental expenses while they exceeded the total per diem and other expenses per travel law of ₱800.00 for claiming hotel accommodation and meal of ₱1,450.00 per day.

Otherwise, the transaction would be considered irregular and refund of the full amount of ₱637,730.00 shall be made in full and immediately.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor and Officials explain the noted observations relative to the implementation of Basudani Festival;

Management observe strictly the austerity measures/prudence in the use of public funds to save funds which can be used to appropriate for programs/projects/   activities that will bring immediate socio-economic benefits among its local constituents;

Former Municipal Mayor submit the liquidation of the cash assistance totaling ₱120,000.00 intended for the elementary and secondary schools in their participation to Basudani Festival which he had received, otherwise refund the full amount;

OIC Accountant and other concerned Officials submit the lacking documents to facilitate audit as to legality and propriety of the disbursements; and

the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer scrutinize the payment of the claims and see to it that it was supported with necessary supporting documents before payment was made.

We recommended that:
the Municipal Mayor create and establish an Inventory Committee, headed by the MGSO with representatives from the Accounting and Assessor’s Office, which will: 
Conduct complete physical inventory of all recorded Municipal properties within a time frame set by the Municipal Mayor;

•	Prepare IIRUP for determined unserviceable properties supported with proper documentation for the subsequent disposal of the same in accordance with COA rules and regulations;
the Property and Accounting Offices prepare Property Cards simultaneous to the inventory taking to facilitate preparation of RPCPPE and reconciliation of records between Property and Accounting Offices. The same should be maintained by both offices to facilitate the recording of future acquisitions and disposal of the properties;

the Accounting and Property Offices conduct periodic reconciliation of property records; and

the Municipal Accountant maintain Property Ledger Cards for each classification of PPE account, make pertinent entries for determined adjustments/errors upon conduct of physical count, create separate subsidiary ledgers for unreconciled amounts, and observe proper disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that:

the  Municipality refrain from granting mobile allowance and rather institute formal internal policies and guidelines, considering who are allowed to be granted, number of postpaid plans allowed, accounting for government asset in cases where in cellular phones and other gadgets were included in the plan,  amount to be charged against government funds, and other pertinent policies and guidelines;

the Municipal Accountant submit the necessary supporting documents required in Item 6.2 of  the Revised Documentary Requirements for Common Government Transactions prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 to prove the accuracy, propriety and validity of the amounts collected and ensure that the same claims in the future be supported with complete documentation.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the:
Municipal Mayor strictly comply and enforce Section 8 of CSC Resolution No. 04-0676 dated June 17, 2004, and as such, file administrative cases and report to the Civil Service Commission those Officials and Employees who continually/habitually delay the liquidation of their cash advances as stated herein, to avoid misapplication and/or personal use of public funds;
Individual Accountable Officers granted with cash advances (a) strictly observe diligence in the liquidation of their respective cash advances within the prescribed period, (b) return the excess cash advances, if any, simultaneously with the liquidation report, and (c) in case of cancelled travel, immediately and fully refund the cash advance and submit valid justification for not pursuing the proposed travel;
Accountable Officers with cash advances ensure that the required supporting documents for the project/activity of different offices are immediately submitted to the Municipal Accountant;
The Municipal Accountant and Treasurer monitor the liquidation of cash advances and issue demand letters to concerned Officials and Employees with cash advances that remained unsettled for more than thirty (30) days; and
The Municipal Treasurer and Accountant (1) withhold the salaries due to Officials and Employees concerned with overdue unliquidated cash advances until full liquidation/settlement has been rendered by the AOs, and (2) prohibit the application of salary deduction as means of settlement for their accountabilities, to prevent misappropriation of public funds, and overstatement of Due from Officers and Employees account and understatement of affected expense accounts for a given period.

