We recommended that the:
HRMO, in the meantime, cautiously monitor and scrutinize logbook entries to ensure proper and accurate recording of attendance actually rendered by municipal employees and officials as well as job orders, and if needed, assign personnel who will closely and strictly monitor logbook entries, and a separate personnel who will monitor the arrival and departure through logging in a separate logbook and personnel to daily conduct parallel inspection of entries of both logbooks;
Municipal Mayor evaluate the previous recommendations of the civil service commission relative to their personnel audit report dated January 15, 2014 and cause for the immediate purchase of the bundy clock / biometric machine and require employees and officials as well as job orders to use the same in registering their actual time of attendance, in order to accurately and systematically monitor daily attendance;
HRMO require all employees and officials as well as job orders to submit the DTRs based on bundy card / biometric print out signed by the immediate supervisor and attach the same to the payroll, to ensure accurate computation of salaries and wages to be paid, thus avoid wastage of government funds thru overpayment or man-hours lost, and
OIC-Municipal Accountant scrutinize the documents supporting the claims and ensure that future claims be supported with complete and valid documentation.

We recommended that the Management prepare Market Development Plan which will serve as guide for the policies and procedures in the operations of the Market since there was still no amendments in the existing Revenue Code and reiterated our recommendations that the:
Municipal Mayor and other officials and employees concerned devise a system or strategy for the effective management of market operations particularly in the proper classification and numbering of market stalls, encouraging the lessees/stallholders to occupy only their leased spaces, and pay their rental fees in a timely manner as provided in the Revenue Code of the Municipality;
Sangguniang Bayan revisit the provisions embodied in the 1994 Revenue Code relative to the market fees and policies and procedures for market operations and make revisions or amendments, when warranted;
Lease of the units of the market stalls in the public market should be covered with Contract of Lease, and MOA for the collection of the stall holders’ counterpart for the improvement of rented stalls to ensure that the terms and conditions agreed upon by both parties will be complied and their interests will be safeguarded; and
Management strictly enforce the collection of fees and corresponding surcharges from the delinquent stallholders and report to the Municipal Accountant the accumulated uncollected amounts for the proper taking up of the uncollected market stall fees that are deemed realizable to reflect the accurate amount of receivable in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Engineer and concerned municipal officials and employees:
include in the Program of Works (POWs) of the projects to implemented by administration  the specific pakyaw work required for the project with the corresponding cost of pakyaw labor;
submit proof of community meetings organized by the project facilitator, if any, and the registration of unemployed or underemployed members of the community who shall be formed into at least three pakyaw groups in case there is competition for the pakyaw works;
present a proof /evidence that pakyaw labor was drawn from the vicinity of the project, or Pakyaw labor groups belong to various barangay associations contiguous to the project site and are recruited within the Barangay/Municipality, as well as the list of workers identified as skilled/semi-skilled/unskilled and their residences which can also be used for future reference;
submit certificate of pakyaw work completed issued by the labor group and certificate of acceptance for pakyaw work completed by the agency; and
strictly comply with the provisions of Section 4(6) of P.D. 1445, Appendix 1 of the RIRR of RA 9184 and Item 4 of the GPPB Resolution No. 018-2006.
